fields.label: Run Consistently in Zone 2
fields.description: Only runs with an average heart rate of 115 bpm or higher count.
fields.objective_definition:
SELECT COALESCE(SUM(EXTRACT(EPOCH FROM ("end" - "start")) / 60), 0)
FROM workouts_workout
WHERE sport_id = 0
AND average_heart_rate >= 115
AND start >= '2025-11-01 06:00:00'
AND "end" <= '2025-12-01 05:59:59'

fields.label: Use the Sauna Regularly
fields.description: Only sauna sessions lasting 15 minutes or longer count.
fields.objective_definition:
SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM workouts_workout
WHERE (sport_id = 233 OR sport_id = -1)
AND EXTRACT(EPOCH FROM ("end" - start)) >= 890
AND start >= '2025-11-01 06:00:00'
AND "end" <= '2025-12-01 05:59:59'

fields.label: Do Basic Strength Training
fields.description: Only sessions lasting more than 20 minutes count.
fields.objective_definition:
SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM workouts_workout
WHERE sport_id = 48
AND (julianday(end) - julianday(start)) * 24 * 60 > 20
AND start >= '2025-11-01 06:00:00'
AND end <= '2025-12-01 05:59:59'

fields.label: Weigh Myself Regularly
fields.description: Each unique day with at least one weigh-in counts (e.g., weighing myself twice in one day only counts as 1 day towards the target).
fields.objective_definition:
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT DATE(measurement_time))
FROM weight_weighin
WHERE measurement_time >= '2025-11-01 06:00:00'
AND measurement_time <= '2025-12-01 05:59:59'

fields.label: Consistently Track the Nutrition I Consume
fields.description: A day's nutrition log only counts if its total logged calories exceed 700 (to prevent getting credit for a nutrition log that I start but fail to finish).
fields.objective_definition:
SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM (
  SELECT DATE(consumption_date) as day, SUM(calories) as total_cal
  FROM nutrition_nutritionentry
  WHERE consumption_date >= '2025-11-01 06:00:00'
  AND consumption_date <= '2025-12-01 05:59:59'
  GROUP BY DATE(consumption_date)
  HAVING SUM(calories) > 700
)

fields.label: Fast Regularly
fields.description: Only fasts lasting 16 hours or longer count.
fields.objective_definition:
SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM fasting_fastingsession
WHERE duration >= 16
AND fast_end_date >= '2025-11-01 06:00:00'
AND fast_end_date <= '2025-12-01 05:59:59'

fields.label: Regularly Pre-Plan My Days (Focuses, Calendar, To Dos)
fields.description: A day only counts if it has at least one "target" defined and it has been scored.

FROM targets_dailyagenda
WHERE date >= '2025-11-01'

fields.label: Lose a Bit of Weight
fields.description: Measured by comparing the average of the first 5 weigh-ins to the average of the last 5. This objective can only be achieved if: (1) I capture 10+ weigh-ins during the month; (2) the first 5 are in the month's first 7 days; (3) the last 5 are in the month's last 7 days.
fields.objective_definition:
WITH month_dates AS (
      SELECT
          '2025-11-01' as month_start,
          '2025-11-30' as month_end
  ),
  weighins_in_month AS (
      SELECT
          DATE(measurement_time) as weigh_date,
          CAST(weight AS REAL) as weight_lbs,
          ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY measurement_time) as row_num
      FROM weight_weighin, month_dates
      WHERE DATE(measurement_time) >= month_dates.month_start
        AND DATE(measurement_time) <= month_dates.month_end
  ),
  first_week AS (
      SELECT * FROM weighins_in_month, month_dates
      WHERE weigh_date <= DATE(month_dates.month_start, '+6 days')
      LIMIT 5
  ),
  last_week AS (
      SELECT * FROM weighins_in_month, month_dates
      WHERE weigh_date >= DATE(month_dates.month_end, '-6 days')
      ORDER BY weigh_date DESC
      LIMIT 5
  ),
  stats AS (
      SELECT
          (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM weighins_in_month) as total_weighins,
          (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM first_week) as first_week_count,
          (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM last_week) as last_week_count,
          (SELECT AVG(weight_lbs) FROM first_week) as first_avg,
          (SELECT AVG(weight_lbs) FROM last_week) as last_avg
  )
  SELECT
      CASE
          WHEN total_weighins >= 10 AND first_week_count = 5 AND last_week_count = 5
          THEN ROUND(first_avg - last_avg, 2)
          ELSE 0.0
      END as weight_loss
  FROM stats

fields.label: Eat Healthy
fields.description: A day counts as healthy if I: log at least 700 calories; stay under 1,500 total calories; stay under 100 grams of carbs.
fields.objective_definition:
SELECT COUNT(*)
  FROM (
      SELECT
          (consumption_date AT TIME ZONE 'America/Chicago')::date as day,
          SUM(calories) as total_calories,
          SUM(carbs) as total_carbs
      FROM nutrition_nutritionentry
      WHERE
          (consumption_date AT TIME ZONE 'America/Chicago')::date >= '2025-11-01'
          AND (consumption_date AT TIME ZONE 'America/Chicago')::date <= '2025-11-30'
      GROUP BY (consumption_date AT TIME ZONE 'America/Chicago')::date
      HAVING
          SUM(calories) >= 700
          AND SUM(calories) < 1500
          AND SUM(carbs) < 110
  ) as healthy_days

fields.excerpt:
Charlie lay awake in the dark, certain she wasnt alone. She could sense him sitting in the chair at the foot of her bed. Watching.

Through the walls she heard the rain falling soft and steady. It had come down like this for days. There was so much of it now all across Manhattan that yesterday Charlie saw a rat floating down her flooded street. The rain had brought wind and the wind had brought a tree branch right through the roof of Charlies bedroom, like a bone through skin. Her father had quickly covered the hole with his old baking tray. Hed duct taped it down, and now, when the rain hit, it pattered soft and hollow like a toy drum.

Charlie knew she needed to break the silence, that she couldnt just lie there pretending to sleep. She tried to find the right words, her fists clenched under the blanket.

This had happened once before, in this same room, fourteen years ago when she was six. She'd woken up and there he was watching her sleep. When shed asked why, her father had said, I just feel like...youre not safe. His hands were shaking.

Charlie looked for a seat, away from the poster, away from the eggs. She spotted one on the other side of the train and edged between backs and elbows, sinking into an open spot across from a young girl mashing buttons on a Game Boy. The girl was dressed as a white rabbit: a headband with felt ears, a cotton tail taped to the back, and a toy pocket watch dangling from a string around her neck.

A woman reached over and gathered the girl's hair into a ponytail. The girl paused her game, and the woman's fingers moved with an easy rhythm, holding a pink elastic hair tie between her teeth. For a moment, the girl closed her eyes.

Charlie watched the ritual. She remembered her father behind her with a brush in his hand when she was about the same agetrying, failing, gentle but clumsy. He'd given up after a few attempts, and after that, Charlie had taught herself in front of the mirrorscared of being the girl with bumps in her hair.

The woman glanced up and caught Charlie staring. She smiled, then her eyes dropped to Charlie's arms, resting on her lap, and her smile flattened. Charlie followed the woman's gaze down to the small white scars running along her forearms. Charlie pulled the sleeves of her hoodie down to her wrists. The woman looked away and finished the ponytail.

Roy shook his head, like he wasn't following.

"Think about it like this... It's the early 1800s and you happen to know that your buddy will be locked up in Alcatraz in 1950. Your goal: bust him out. The prison's not built yet, but the island exists, right?"

Roy just stared back.

"So you change the land nowdig passages, hide toolsleave a ghost in the dirt that'll still be there a hundred years later."

Roy looked back at the strange bird, staring at it for a long moment.

"I'm no good with my hands, Roy. And I can't trust anyone else. I need you. Again."

Roy sighed, then drew in a breath to speak, when

BOOM.

A sharp explosion rattled the diner's floor and shuddered the windows. The smell of burning oil filled the restaurant. Through the glass, an orange blast punched out of an open bay at Dale's Garage, heat shimmering the air before it was swallowed by black smoke.

In Ethan Rothschilds study, the metronome on the desk carved up silence with surgical precision. It went click click click as its silver pendulum swung back and forth. Charlies father could notwould notwrite without this sound. He needed it to coax his mind into that foggy, fertile place where stories took shape. In here, the metronome was always working, even when he wasnt.

Charlie was slumped into the leather chair in the corner, feeling defeated after nearly an hour of searching for a hidden room that she no longer believed existed. Shed tried it all: pushed on panels, hunted for switches, even tilted books on the shelf. Nothing gave.

In her hand was Bear, the teddy bear Charlie had had since before she could remember. Whenever she was worried or anxious, she found Bear, and tonight was no different. He had one red eye and one blue eyea factory flaw, her father had said. But he thought it made Bear special. Unique, he'd said. Charlie ran her fingers down the long stitch in Bear's right foot, where her father had sewn the torn mohair back together after she'd caught it on a fence when she was seven. Bear knew all of Charlie's secrets.

Charlie knew that sound. It was a film projector, rattling softly from somewhere above her. She had no idea where she was, how long she'd been unconscious, or if down was still downbut she knew that sound.

As a kid, when she'd gone to the movies with her dad, Charlie would sometimes stare up at the projection booth. She liked the way it looked, perched in its little room, creating meaning from light. That felt like magic.

Wherever she was now, the ground beneath her felt soft and it smelled like dust. Charlie searched for the word. It took a while to find: carpet. She was lying facedown on a thick shag carpet, sunken deep into it, almost swallowed.

Charlie wasn't sure what had brokenher or the world. She felt like her brain had been taken apart by some cosmic mechanic who'd forgotten how it all fit back together. She had a dull awareness that something impossible had happened back in her father's hidden room. And she knew that wherever she was now, it was very, very far from home.

Slowly, Charlie opened her eyes, lifted her head, and looked around.

It was a theater.

Then Charlie saw a tower-like device. Or ratherthe tower saw her, and kicked into motion.

On the desk, next to the clock, was a tower of glass and metalabout two feet tall, shaped like a column. Its surface was transparent, its machinery visible inside: tiny gears, levers, and shutters nested in delicate layers around a narrow spiral chute no wider than a marble. It looked both futuristic and antique. As Charlie stepped closer, the tower stirred to life: its inner gears beginning to turn, its interior filling with light.

Charlie was clevershe'd always been cleverbut it didn't take cleverness to understand what to do next. The design of the tower made that much clear. From her pocket, Charlie pulled the purple marble she'd scavenged from Tally's innards. She held it between two fingers and lifted it toward the top of the tower, where a small opening waited, perfectly shaped for it.

The moment she set the marble into place, the tower seemedpleased. Its internal machinery whirred faster, light deep inside shifting through shades of white and blue and gold. The marble began to rotate, slow at first, soon faster. And thenjust like in that board game Mousetrap, which Charlie had played only once as a kid before losing all the piecesthe marble dropped into the tower, slipping down its spiral chute, through a maze of tiny doors and shifting panels, round and round until, at last, it disappeared.

This invite is for anyone in IT who executes or manages change and/or uses the Change Management module in ServiceNow or the Unplanned Outage Notifications.   Every Tuesday morning from 7:30-8:00 AM (Central) this meeting will be held to discuss the upcoming planned changes for the week and go over the previous weeks unplanned outages (UPON's).
 
What is this meeting for?
This meeting is intended for notification and informational purposes only.  The idea is to get as many IT people together to discuss the upcoming changes, recent unplanned outages, collaborate and essentially offer a forum where the IT community can see the upcoming activities that may impact the business or their own area. 
 
Who should attend this meeting?
First and foremost, this meeting is mandatory if you are the requestor or assignee of a planned change for the upcoming week, regardless of the risk or type of change.  You need to be prepared to discuss your change and answer any questions should they arise.  If you cannot attend, please have someone attend in your place.
Or alternatively, you simply want to stay informed on upcoming changes in the IT world.   Feel free to come join us, even if you have no planned changes for the week.  The meeting is cross-functional, informational, and even sometimes entertaining.
 
Who will run this extremely important and informative meeting?
Carol Davis will host this meeting from week to week.  Contact either Carol Davis or An Tran if you have any questions.
